<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   TV: Goodwill Gold, China's
   Bigfoot, Straight-Talking Cops
   ----
   By Dorothy Rabinowitz
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<LP>
   Saturday, Aug. 4, 3:05 p.m.-6:05 p.m. and 8 p.m.-1:05 a.m.
EDT, on TBS: Last weekend of the Goodwill Games. Saturday
competitions include gold-medal boxing; women's basketball
and hockey semifinals. Finals in women's figure skating and
men's volleyball in the evening. Sunday, 3:05 p.m.-6:05 p.m.:
Women's basketball, hockey and boxing finals. 8:05 p.m.-1:05
a.m. More boxing finals, judo, closing ceremonies. Caution:
If Montgomery Clift or some other film star appears on your
screen instead of the above-mentioned gymkhana, it's because
some cable systems, truckling to the public's demonstrable
lack of interest in sports as geopolitical sermon, will be
airing movies instead of the games.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sunday, Aug. 5, 8-9 p.m. EDT, on Arts &amp; Entertainment:
"Crew of the Enola Gay." A return to Hiroshima with some of
the air crew who dropped the bomb in August of 1945. Jaunty
men in their late 60s and 70s, the visitors are anxious and
awestruck as they arrive. Still, the very British narrator
has trouble concealing a note of supercilious distaste for
these Air Force veterans who calmly swallow dinner and talk
quietly among themselves and who clearly are, in the
narrator's view, insufficiently guilt-ridden. The narrator
problem aside, there is much here that is rivetingly
complicated as the unfailingly gracious Japanese welcome
these Americans. If nothing else this would be worth seeing
for the exchange between the veterans and some survivors of
radiation sickness, both for what is said and the infinite
suggestiveness of what is left unsaid.
                                                                                                       

   Monday, Aug. 6, 8-9 pm EDT, on PBS (PBS air dates and
times vary so check local listings): "Wild Man of China."
Alleged sightings of a half-human, apelike creature tempt two
American anthropologists on a journey through central China.
The trip is an education in a number of ways. One learns
something about medical standards in the People's Republic of
China, when an explorer needing medical treatment tries to
get a hospital doctor to see the wisdom of using a clean
hypodermic needle. But the trip up, or perhaps it is down,
the Yangtze to look for Wild Man, as he is fondly known, is
enchanting because Wild Man (said by one and all villagers to
have long red hair) clearly has picked a splendid part of
China to haunt. The scenes in the marketplaces and the
closeups of the townspeople who have never before seen
Westerners, are memorable. Wild Man is never found,
fortunately for him, and the 2,000-year-old hunt goes on.
                                                                                                       

   Wednesday, Aug. 8, 9-11 p.m. EDT, on PBS: "Castro's Cuba:
Two Views." Two views indeed. One is from Cuban exile and
photography director Nestor Almendros ("Kramer vs. Kramer,"
"Sophie's Choice") and journalist Jorge Ulla. It shows
witness after witness to the torture and decades of
imprisonment Castro visited on dissidents. That torture took
place, they remind us, while progressive intellectuals and
literary types in the U.S. and elsewhere busied themselves
celebrating Castro, hence the title, "Nobody Listened." The
other film, "Uncompromising Revolution," is a worshipful
portrait of Castro's Cuba put together by Saul Landau of the
Institute for Policy Studies. In it we are privileged to see
pictures of baby Fidel, Fidel at school, and also pictures
galore of singing and happy Cubans. Indeed the film is cast
mainly with smiling and happy Cubans and happy children
singing, as happy livestock wander by. The Maximum Leader
himself also is merry. No viewer comparing this work with
Messrs. Almendros and Ulla's detailed documentation of horror
will have any trouble deciding which has the ring of truth.
                                                                                                       

   Wednesday, Aug. 8, 10-11 p.m. EDT, on CBS: "Top Cops," a
superior documentary series about police, the appeal of which
derives from a good ear, unsensational re-enactments, and a
lack of pretension. Its creators appear to be aware that when
extraordinary experiences of ordinary people, like policemen,
are rendered in the way that those ordinary people actually
talk, the result can be powerful. A cop program in which
police talk like normal human beings rather than cosmopolitan
wits is to be cherished.
                                                                                                       

   Monday, Aug. 13, 8-10 pm EDT, on TNT: "Heat Wave." A
singularly demagogic portrait of the 1965 Watts riots that
left 35 people dead, 30 of them black. It may be worth
watching as an example of just how much vicious stereotyping
it still is possible to get away with now, so long as the
stereotyping is directed at the right group. Here is a film
in which every black, without exception, is heroic, highly
sensitive, loving and family-minded. Every white, without
exception, is either a cold, vicious redneck, a selfish
hypocrite, infantile or cowardly. They used to call this sort
of stereotyping racism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900802-0147
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900802-0147.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Notable &amp; Quotable
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST DJ
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Following is an editorial from last Friday's Bangkok Post.
It refers to the Asian-Pacific Economic Cooperation meeting
held in Singapore earlier this week:
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The chief subject of corridor discussions at a conference
in Singapore this weekend on the economy of Pacific nations
will focus on Southeast Asia's longest-running war without
bloodshed. Singapore's tireless dispute with the foreign
Press has escalated again. The government has barred
reporters from the region's two leading economic publications
from covering the Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation
conference. By keeping away The Asian Wall Street Journal and
the Far Eastern Economic Review, Singapore has assured
diluting serious discussion about the region's economy.
Delegates, including senior regional and international
ministers, will be debating and discussing the Press ban.
Indeed, it will be a major topic when U.S. Secretary of State
James Baker meets Singapore Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew.
   From a simple assertion of government rights, Singapore's
unrelenting pursuit of certain media and correspondents has
intensified to this. With their circulations severely
restricted, the two publications are effectively barred from
the vast majority of the Singapore public and visitors to the
Republic. The issue has consumed a large amount of Mr. Lee's
time and that of his deputy and appointed successor Goh Chok
Tong. The hard-line, no-compromise stance of Mr. Lee's
government has made Singapore appear petty in the eyes of
many. These certainly include many executives who do business
in, or with, the island republic.
   In all of this, the Press has become the underdog.
Predictably, it has gained much public sympathy, if not
outright support. By continuing its public battles with two
of the region's leading business publications, Singapore has
cast itself in the role of persecutor as well as prosecutor.
Neither of these is a role desirable for the Singapore
government in this instance.
   It is possible, certainly, to consider Singapore's
position in the dispute. Mr. Lee and his government maintain
they have the right to bar access to reporters of media they
consider unfriendly. Of course they do. But the disputes in
these cases have sunk to making picayune and obscure points.
The fact is that neither publication, for example, has called
for the ouster of the Singapore Government, let alone its
overthrow. The full-page advertisement {a reprint of an
editorial that ran in the Asian Journal July 23 explaining
the company's position} in Tuesday's Asian Wall Street
Journal left many readers wondering how two eminently
sensible organizations -- the newspaper and the Singapore
Government -- could be reduced to such bickering.
   They can be excused for asking if this is a tempest in a
teacup. Mr. Goh has made it clear that reporters from the
parent organizations of both publications may cover the
weekend conference. Only those employed specifically by their
Asian partners are banned. Thus, to many, it will seem that
there is neither a crime nor a punishment. The physical
barring of reporters is therefore more puzzling than ever.
   The Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation Conference is a
major international meeting. Current practice in almost every
country, and quite correctly so, is to allow the Press to
cover such meetings. Singapore neither helps its own case
nor, in the end, the publications it seeks to punish. By
barring serious economic reporters from a serious economic
conference, the Singapore Government succeeds only in
appearing oppressive, hardly the judgment it seeks. That the
outside world cares little about the specific reasons for
such action only further hurts Singapore's image.
   Mr. Lee and Mr. Goh, both statesmen of the world class,
can perform better than this. Most governments in the world
have come to a truce, however uneasy, with foreign newsmen
without either giving up their own rights, or forcing
reporters to give up their claims to cover news as they and
their publications see fit. The Singapore Press dispute has
dragged on for years. Instead of seeking impossible redress
for events in a past long forgotten by the public, Singapore
might well consider calling a truce and looking to the future
in this matter. A fine, diplomatic beginning would be for
Singapore to make a quick reversal and allow reporters from
the two publications to attend this weekend's very important
meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
