<HL>
   Twentieth Century Fox
   Is Sued by `Aliens' Group
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NWS
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The star, director and producers of the hit
science-fiction film "Aliens" filed suit against Twentieth
Century Fox Film Corp., charging that the movie company
didn't pay them their fair share of the profit.
   The suit was filed in Los Angeles Superior Court by
actress Sigourney Weaver, director James Cameron, producer
Gail Anne Hurd and executive producers Gordon Carroll, Walter
Hill and David Giler. They alleged that Fox failed to include
all the film's revenue in account statements and made
improper expense deductions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fox, a unit of Australia-based News Corp., also allegedly
set aside improper and excess reserves and provided
inaccurate accountings, the suit charged.
   The complaint seeks unspecified damages, a judicial
determination that the film is now in net profit and an
accounting. Ms. Weaver claims she was to receive 10% of the
1986 film's net profit. "Aliens" was the sequel to the 1979
science fiction hit, "Alien," about monsters in deep space.
   A spokesman for Fox said the company had no comment on the
suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900802-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900802-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foley Condemns the IRA
   For Killing of Politician
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Speaker Thomas Foley, in a strongly worded
statement to the full House, condemned the "terror tactics"
of the Irish Republican Army and "cowardly murder" of Ian
Gow, a British conservative killed this week by a bomb
planted in his car.
   "The clear and despicable purpose of this callous act was
intimidation through terror," said the Washington State
Democrat, who broke with custom by speaking from the well of
the House immediately after the chamber convened yesterday.
Surprised by the speaker's appearance, members sat in unusual
silence but then rose in applause at the conclusion of his
remarks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The IRA's guns and bombs have not brought independence
for Northern Ireland, nor will they," said Mr. Foley, one of
the most prominent Irish-American officeholders in the U.S.
"What they have brought -- in the years since British troops
were sent to Northern Ireland in 1972 -- is the deaths of
many more civilian bystanders than of soldiers or policemen,
the deaths of many more Catholics than Protestants, in fact,
many more deaths than can be attributed to the British."
   A supporter of the 1985 Anglo-Irish accord giving the
Republic of Ireland a consultative role in the governing of
Northern Ireland, Mr. Foley has disagreed with Mr. Gow on a
number of Irish issues. But he was described as deeply
affected by the killing and the threat it posed to
Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
