<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Unilateral Branch Disarmament
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Let's see if we understand the new system. The President's
thoughts about budget cuts on domestic issues are irrelevant,
but if Congress targets strategic programs for oblivion the
Commander in Chief can do nothing about it. President Bush
plans a speech today to salvage the Pentagon budget, but it
may be too little too late.
   Chairman Les Aspin led the charge when his House Armed
Services Committee slashed $24 billion from the Bush defense
budget of $307 billion. This includes chopping nearly $2
billion from SDI's $4.7 billion proposal and the elimination
of the entire B-2 Stealth Bomber program.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stealth won't be coming up on anyone's radar screen if the
House committee has its way. The committee voted to eliminate
the entire program after the 15 planes already authorized are
built. This drove Rep. Ron Dellums, the Berkeley dove, into
deep rapture. "I've been awake since about 4:30 this morning
trying to come to grips with what we've done," he said
yesterday. "I was out running at 6 this morning just because
I was exhilarated."
   The Senate may salvage some of the worst cuts, but its
price may be the death of strategic defense. Democrats
Richard Shelby and Jeff Bingaman plan to offer an amendment
on the Senate floor this week that would deny President Bush
the option of deploying SDI anytime this decade. Not
coincidentally, the amendment would steer SDI money to
projects in the senators' states, Alabama and New Mexico.
   Senator Sam Nunn once suggested he'd support this
amendment, but now is having second thoughts. Significantly,
he wants to see enough money spent to adequately test
Brilliant Pebbles, the little satellites that might one day
intercept incoming missiles. "We have to look at that
technology," Mr. Nunn told us yesterday, since it may have
other important uses such as communications. This is welcome
news, though we can't agree with him that SDI needs more
"line-item and management guidance" from Congress. When has
any weapon benefited from Congressional micromanagement?
   There is plenty for President Bush to say about American
defenses. He might note that for all the changes, there is no
evidence that the Soviet Union has slowed its military
spending by one soft ruble. SS-24 and SS-25 nuclear missiles
still roll down the assembly line, pointing at the U.S.
   Even if the Cold War eventually thaws on the Soviet side
as well, Congress has taken aim at the very defense systems
that make sense in a world where the typical threat is posed
by places such as Libya and Iraq. Stealth is designed to slip
nuclear weapons by Soviet radar, but with its 10,000-mile
range can also get conventional weapons to anywhere in the
world. SDI becomes more important as each tinpot dictator
inevitably gets his hands on ballistic missiles.
   Strategy obviously means one thing to Pentagon planners
and quite another to doves in Congress. It was a commitment
to strength that forced the Soviets to begin to change their
ways. This is no time to declare victory and announce
disarmament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900802-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900802-0121.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bush, Risking Partisan Budget Scrap,
   Threatens to Stop Being Kinder, Gentler
   ----
   By David Wessel and Jeffrey H. Birnbaum
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush, risking a partisan firefight
that could destroy the chances for a budget compromise this
fall, is threatening to step up his attacks on the Democrats.
   Although Mr. Bush himself said nothing publicly yesterday,
he told congressional Republicans he is prepared to alter his
tactics and criticize Democrats for standing in the way of a
budget compromise.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Brother, he's got fire in his belly," said House
Republican Leader Robert Michel of Illinois. The president is
"certainly not going to keep his trap shut all during
August."
   Although House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia
said he is advising Mr. Bush and his aides to realize "that
their opponents are not people of good will," other
Republican budget negotiators and administration officials
insist Mr. Bush hasn't given up on the bipartisan budget
summit yet.
   Instead, they say the administration has chosen to walk a
fine line: criticizing Democrats without being so harsh that
it becomes impossible to resume negotiations after the August
congressional recess. One senior GOP congressional aide
predicted Mr. Bush will temper his criticism if Democrats
agree this week to a firm timetable for reaching an agreement
in September. Negotiations for such a timetable are
continuing.
   Nevertheless, the prospect of a month of partisan attacks
and counterattacks led to more pessimism on Capitol Hill
about the chances of reaching an accord before
across-the-board spending cuts are triggered on Oct. 15.
   "It's going to make it very difficult to arrive at a
negotiated settlement if the administration deliberately
poisons the political atmosphere over the next few weeks,
which they seem intent on doing," said Sen. Jim Sasser (D.,
Tenn.), chairman of the Senate Budget Committee.
   Sen. Pete Domenici, senior Republican on that committee,
conceded: "The odds of us not being able to get it done are
increased over two weeks ago." But the New Mexico Republican
added: "I clearly believe it's doable in September."
   "I think the first half of the summit has collapsed," Rep.
Gingrich said outside the White House yesterday, adding: "I
think the president is committed to trying to resurrect it in
September."
   The only way to avoid triggering the deep spending cuts
mandated by the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law will be to
alter the law, an option the administration says it will
veto, or to wrap up a compromise immediately after Labor Day
and rush it through Congress -- which remains a possibility.
   "I'm quite optimistic when we get back here (from the
August break) you'll see a serious exchange of offers," said
Lloyd Bentsen (D., Texas), chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee. Despite yesterday's rhetoric, negotiators are
still contemplating several days of intense talks in the
first week of September.
   Mr. Bush and his congressional allies have been backed
into a corner by the Democrats and by their own missteps.
President Bush in June said he was willing to raise taxes,
repudiating his campaign promise without extracting any
substantial concessions from Democrats. A month later, bitter
House Republicans demanded that the summit eschew any tax
increases. And then last week, widely reported leaks of a
draft Republican proposal painted the party as favoring
higher taxes on beer, wine and liquor, along with limits on
deductions for state and local income taxes.
   Almost immediately, some Republican negotiators began
disavowing parts of the plan. Now that Mr. Bush has elected
not to demand that Congress delay or cancel its August
recess, a course that some of his advisers suggested, the
only ammunition he has left is harsh rhetoric.
   Democrats, meanwhile, have kept their own substantial
internal divisions quiet and haven't endorsed any unpopular
proposals -- either in public or, much to the frustration of
the Republicans, at the closed-door budget summit. "By our
silence, we have been successful in the summit so far," said
Dan Rostenkowski (D., Ill.), chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee.
   "The Republicans have just shot themselves in the foot, in
the neck, in the ear," he added. "They're masochists."
   Rep. Gingrich agrees. The summit has been like "watching
the Republicans punch themselves in the face," he said. So
far, the political costs have fallen on the Republicans. But
he added: "The political costs aren't over. It's like
measuring World War II right after Pearl Harbor."
   Under the Gramm-Rudman law, spending cuts of about $85
billion -- or perhaps as much as $100 billion depending on
certain technical factors -- will be triggered on Oct. 15
unless Congress passes legislation bringing the
administration's deficit forecast below $110 billion before
then. By all accounts, the spending cuts would be so deep
that the federal government would have to lay off employees
and reduce services -- although it isn't completely clear how
quickly that would happen.
   While the budget negotiators have been bickering, Congress
has been proceeding with spending bills that would add to the
deficit rather than reduce it. Congressional Republicans said
Mr. Bush vowed to veto them yesterday. "When the spending
bills come to him which are in excess of what he has
proposed, he has made up his mind to issue the vetoes," said
Rep. Bill Frenzel (R., Minn.).
   ---
   Rodney Ferguson contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
