<HL>
   International:
   Spain's Rediscovery of Latin America
   Spurs Hopes of Cooperation, Partnership
   ----
   By Nicholas Bray
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   MADRID -- With his back to a portrait of Simon Bolivar,
the man who led Latin America's struggle for independence in
the early 1800s, Fernando Valenzuela reviews relations with
Spain's former New World colonies.
   "For the first time in its history," affirms Mr.
Valenzuela, the head of Spain's overseas-development agency,
"Spain can be of use to Latin America."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And, he might well add, Latin America can be of use to
Spain.
   Nearly five centuries after Christopher Columbus, Spain is
rediscovering Latin America. But this time, it is seeking
partnership and cooperation rather than empire.
   In part, its aim is assisting Latin American development.
But there is a measure of self-interest as well. Spanish
firms are looking to the region for expansion. And Spanish
diplomats and officials are dreaming of an Ibero-American
community of nations.
   "If Spain has any area of influence and contacts, it's in
Latin America," says Pina Lopez Gay, the executive vice
chairman of Spain's commission for commemorating the 500th
anniversary of Columbus's arrival in America in 1492.
   "For any Spaniard," says Candido Velazquez-Gaztelu,
chairman of Telefonica de Espana S.A., "Latin America is the
prolongation of our own land. Our peoples have the same
language, the same culture. There are great opportunities for
us to do business together."
   However, despite such ties and the family links forged by
cross-migration, "there are a lot of misunderstandings on
both sides," says Pedro Shimose, a Bolivian writer who lives
in Madrid.
   Spain, though still "la madre patria", or mother country,
for many Latin Americans, is viewed by large numbers in the
region with mixed affection and contempt. Tales of the
cruelty of the Spanish conquistadors and of the Latin
American fight for independence still foster resentment. On
the Spanish side, years of post-colonial prejudice are summed
up in the word "sudaca", used dismissively by Spaniards to
refer to their South American cousins.
   "We have had a strange love-hate relationship," says
Emilio Cassinello, a former Spanish ambassador to Mexico.
"Perhaps it's because we haven't been able to digest past
history."
   As part of its drive for closer ties, Spain is offering
aid, trade and political cooperation to its former colonies.
And it has taken on a role as their advocate and protector in
relations with Western Europe. The bottom line, in both
cases, is Spain's search for a greater world role.
   There are signs that Spain is winning increased
international credibility because of its links with Latin
America. Though Spain was sharply critical of the U.S.
military intervention in Panama, U.S. officials say
Washington pays heed to Madrid's views on the region.
   In October and February, Spain was host for two rounds of
talks between Britain and Argentina that led them to mend
diplomatic relations torn by the 1982 war over the Falkland
Islands. Spain also provided facilities for talks -- albeit
inconclusive ones -- between warring factions in Guatemala.
   Spain's 1992 Columbus celebration is providing a major
impulse for its Ibero-American community plans. As part of
the buildup, Spain has launched a series of projects with
Latin America, including a multivolume history of
Ibero-America, the repair of historic monuments in Latin
America and a Spanish-language patent registry.
   Loosely modeled on Britain's Commonwealth and France's
ties with Francophone Africa, Spain's vision of an
Ibero-American community still lacks any institutional
framework.
   From his office on the outskirts of Madrid, Mr. Valenzuela
manages an aid budget of less than $100 million a year, more
than half of which goes to the poorest of Latin American
countries. Until the early 1980s, Spain was an aid recipient
itself. Now, its economy is booming and it can afford to
share its wealth.
   On the commercial front, while Spanish firms start with a
linguistic advantage, they face tough competition from other
countries. The U.S., West Germany, Italy and France all have
stronger commercial ties with the region.
   But many companies are hoping to change the situation.
"Until now, we haven't taken as much commercial advantage of
our links with Latin America as we should have," says
Telefonica's Mr. Velazquez-Gaztelu. In addition to buying
into the telephone systems of Chile and Argentina this year,
Telefonica is interested in Mexico, Venezuela and Puerto
Rico.
   Last month, the Spanish airline Iberia led a consortium
that was the sole bidder for a stake in Aerolineas
Argentinas, and Repsol, the Spanish state oil company, has
linked up with Petroleos Mexicanos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900802-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900802-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   World Wire
   ----
   Compiled by William Mathewson
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST CCI EUROP HMC
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
AIRLINES (AIR)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
MASS TRANSIT, BUS LINES, SUBWAYS, HIGHWAYS (TRA)
</IN>
<LP>
   A LOAN FOR BANGLADESH
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bangladesh has secured its first major commercial loan and
thus may have improved the chances for attracting additional
foreign investment.
   The $100 million loan is part of a $435 million financing
package for a fertilizer plant that is expected to increase
substantially the country's exports when it is completed in
three years. The package also includes a complex mix of
foreign-export credits, government concessions, investments
by equity partners and political-risk insurance.
   Citicorp International Ltd., the Hong Kong arm of the U.S.
bank, coordinated the loan, which involves the participation
of 10 banks. Bankers say it was the project's merits rather
than new-found confidence in Bangladesh's economy that
persuaded them to make the loan.
   The Bangladesh Parliament passed a bill granting
citizenship to foreign nationals who deposit $1 million or
more in a Bangladeshi financial institution.
                                                                                                       

   HELPING SOUTH KOREA'S FARMERS
                                                                                                       

   The South Korean government strongly opposes the opening
of its agricultural markets to foreign exporters, a top Seoul
official said. Lee Kie Choo, assistant foreign minister for
economic affairs, said the country has a fragile and
vulnerable farming sector requiring protection for some time
to come. He said he doubted the government would open the
rice market to imports within 10 years.
                                                                                                       

   PARIS METRO CRACKDOWN

   The operators of the Paris Metro said they would clear the
subway system's corridors of the 2,000 vendors who illegally
sell wares to commuters from makeshift stands. A Metro
spokeswoman said transit-authority police would seize the
fruit, sunglasses and plastic toys offered for sale by the
vendors, who are mainly Third World immigrants. Prior
attempts had failed because the sellers had only been served
with summonses that they often failed to pay, she said.
                                                                                                       

   INDIAN CRASH REPORT
                                                                                                       

   Pilot error and lack of guidance from air-traffic
controllers led to the 1988 crash of an Indian Airlines plane
that killed all but two of the 135 people on board, a report
said. An Indian news agency quoted the report from a
government-appointed inquiry as saying there was no
structural or mechanical failure involved in the crash of the
17-year-old jet. The Boeing 737, on a flight from Bombay to
the western state of Gujarat, crashed in fog while
approaching the airport.
                                                                                                       

   A SUMMIT IN VENICE
                                                                                                       

   Meeting in Venice, the leaders of Italy, Czechoslovakia,
Austria, Hungary and Yugoslavia reached a wide range of
accords, most of which involved improving transportation
links among the countries. The five nations are members of
the Pentagonal Initiative, a regional alliance founded in
Budapest last November. Officials said the alliance could
bring East European countries closer to the European
Community and act as a counterweight to a unified Germany.
                                                                                                       

   HONDA'S CHINA PLANS
                                                                                                       

   Japan's Honda Motor Co. is expanding its
motorcycle-service network in China and establishing
technical schools there for mechanics. Honda, which ranks
first in the world in motorcycle sales, now has service
centers in four Chinese cities. It plans to join three
Chinese motorcycle companies in setting up an extensive
service network throughout the country. Over the past three
years, the number of motorcycles in China doubled to about
five million units, Honda said.
                                                                                                       

   DEFENDING AUSTRALIA
                                                                                                       

   Australians have an underlying fear of foreign invasion,
and partly privatizing the nation's defense force could help
allay concern, according to a report by the Australian
Defense Department.
   The report, part of a drive to involve the public in
defense matters, seeks formation of a new militia and the
transfer to civilians of jobs now held by the military.
   "If our strategic outlook were to deteriorate, the
underlying paranoia Australians still harbor about foreign
attack could reappear," the report said. It said further that
actively involving Australia's civilians should end "the
malaise which causes many in the community to feel their
country cannot be defended."
   The report recommended cutting regular army, navy and
air-force strength to 47,000 from nearly 70,000, supplemented
by a 52,000-member militia conscripted for short-term
military roles. The number of civilians doing work for the
defense force on contract, such as warehousing and food
supply, would be raised to 38,000 from 15,000.
                                                                                                       

   POSTSCRIPTS . . .
                                                                                                       

   A survey of 500 Japanese business people visiting the
information museum of IBM Japan in Tokyo showed that Japanese
workers generally feel uneasy about taking long summer
vacations. Four out of five said they worried that a lot of
work would be piled up when they returned to their office
after a vacation and one in four said they phoned their
office to ask how work was going during their holidays. . . .
Italy's Undersecretary of Finance Stefano De Luca, responding
to a query in Parliament as to why the government was
ignoring prostitutes' earnings, explained that prostitution
isn't a recognized profession on tax forms and thus isn't
subject to income or sale taxes.
