<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE ECONOMY REMAINS stagnant, three monthly reports
suggest. The leading indicators index and construction
spending were unchanged in June, and the purchasers' index of
manufacturing health fell in July. The data fueled
speculation by some about a possible recession.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices rose on the gloomy economic reports, as did
utility stocks and gold. Stocks in general slumped, while the
dollar reversed its slide.
   ---
   Kodak's profit jumped in the second quarter, as cost
cutting yielded savings sooner than analysts expected. The
company's stock surged $4.25 to close at $42.375 a share.
   ---
   IBM will set up its office-products business as a separate
unit, preparing for its sale to Clayton &amp; Dubilier for a sum
estimated at nearly $2.3 billion. The deal will enable IBM to
cut its staff by nearly 6,000 people.
   ---
   Salomon plans further cutbacks at its Philipp Brothers
commodity firm and may consider selling the unprofitable
unit, Salomon executives say.
   ---
   Chicago Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann resigned
after weeks of criticism of his role as head of financially
crippled Stotler Group. Vice Chairman William O'Connor was
elected to succeed Mahlmann.
   ---
   The thrift-bailout agency intends to accelerate its sale
of seized S&amp;L assets, targeting $50 billion by year end.
   ---
   AT&amp;T, Nynex and Ameritech plan to develop a radio
technology that could significantly increase the capacity of
cellular radio systems.
   ---
   Pathe Cinema will remain French, as Giancarlo Parretti and
Banque Rivaud agreed to sell it to Chargeurs for $207.3
million, ending Parretti's bid to buy all of the film
company.
   ---
   A $54 billion farm bill cleared the House. The five-year
measure would end a decline in income supports, but tighten
limits on aid to individuals.
   ---
   Japan agreed to give U.S. firms more opportunities to sell
telecommunications gear and data-transmission services to
Japanese customers.
   ---
   Oil prices soared on reports of renewed tension between
Iraq and Kuwait. The price of crude for delivery next month
jumped 85 cents a barrel.
   ---
   Bush is threatening to step up attacks on Democrats about
the budget, which could hurt chances of a deficit-cutting
compromise this fall.
   ---
   Washington Bancorp. of D.C. sought protection from
creditors. The firm expects that holders "will be unable to
realize value" for their stock.
   ---
   Purchase prices for small firms fell further in the first
half of this year, as regulators and recession fears led
banks to tighten financing.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 176,810,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2899.26, off 5.94; transportation 1091.06, off 2.37;
utilities 212.90, up 2.89.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3508.29, up
21.00.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.52, off 0.38;
spot index 131.89, off 0.36.
   Dollar: 147.18 yen, up 1.38; 1.5885 marks, up 0.0016.
</TEXT>
