</DOCID>
<HL>
   Loews Net Fell 41%
   In Quarter Amid Skid
   In Insurance Business
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LTR
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Loews Corp.'s second-quarter net income fell
41%, reflecting a 58% profit drop at its insurance business.
   Analysts said the fall in earnings in the insurance
business was expected. They were surprised, however, by the
15% drop in Loews's tobacco profit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Second-period net dropped to $192.9 million, or $2.60 a
share, from $329 million, or $4.38 a share, a year earlier.
The results also reflect a loss from realized investments of
$16.8 million, or 23 cents a share, compared with gains of
$61.5 million, or 82 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue at Loews, which has interests in hotels, watches,
ships and insurance, among other things, grew 3.4% to $3.09
billion from $2.99 billion.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, Loews shares
dropped $4.50 to $99.75 on heavy volume of 643,000 shares.
   Earnings from the CNA Financial insurance business dropped
to $70.4 million from $169.5 million. The tobacco business,
which generates about 50% of the parent's profit, saw
earnings fall 15% to $104.5 million from the year-earlier
$122.8 million.
   "I wasn't expecting a shortfall in the tobacco business,"
said Diana K. Temple, analyst at Salomon Brothers Inc. "The
earnings were about 40 cents less than I thought." The
company attributed the lower earnings at the Lorillard
tobacco operation to a drop in demand after prices were
raised in May.
   Loews also said it had purchased in the open market about
952,000 of its common shares during the past six months and
said it intends to buy additional shares periodically. At
June 30, Loews had an average 74.1 million shares
outstanding, down 1.3% from a year earlier.
   For the six months, Loews said net fell 22% to $416.6
million, or $5.60 a share, from $533.5 million, or $7.08 a
share, for the like 1989 period. Revenue rose 8.3% to $6.07
billion from $5.61 billion.
   The latest six-month results reflect a gain of $70.2
million, or 94 cents a share, on the sale of three oil
tankers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900802-0011
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900802-0011.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Southern Pacific Ends
   Bid for Soo Rail Line,
   Gets Trackage Rights
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
08/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BNI CP T.CP CNW
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Southern Pacific Transportation Co. said it terminated an
agreement with Soo Line Railroad Co. to purchase Soo's rail
line connecting Kansas City and Chicago; however, the company
said it reached a trackage rights agreement with Burlington
Northern Inc. that would give it a Chicago route.
   Financially troubled Southern Pacific, a San Francisco
unit of Denver-based Rio Grande Industries, had sought to
acquire its own direct rail route to Chicago to better
compete with Western rail rivals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the company said it failed to gain the consent of
Chicago &amp; North Western Transportation Co., which has joint
ownership of a small portion of the line. Southern Pacific
had planned to spend $86 million to purchase the 532-mile
route from Soo and another $50 million to renovate the track
over three years.
   Having called off the agreement to purchase the line,
Southern Pacific said it reached a trackage rights agreement
with Burlington Northern. Under the agreement, Southern
Pacific will operate trains with its own locomotives and
crews on Burlington Northern's 466-mile route between Kansas
City and Chicago. Southern Pacific declined to discuss terms.
   Soo Line, a wholly owned subsidiary of Canadian Pacific
Ltd., said the proposed sale of its line to Southern Pacific
had received unanimous approval from the Interstate Commerce
Commission. But Soo said it faced "excessive economic
demands" from Chicago &amp; North Western for consent to Soo's
transfer of ownership of a 37-mile portion of the line. CNW
Corp., Chicago &amp; North Western's parent, declined to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
